node.text: Talking today with Derrick from @blackandbrightin2nd about Zaretta Hammond’s Culturally Responsive Teaching and the Brain. Reasons why CRT work is so important and highlighting some important parts of the book. If you have not already read it, I highly suggest that you do. It’s powerful, it’s important, and it’s truly best practices. #CulturallyResponsiveTeaching #CognitiveScience #teachersofinstagram #teacherlife

node.text:
Talking organization today in my stories! Here’s the compact version:
My rainbow ten drawer cart helps me keep organized. It helps piles from forming and taking up space.
Let me tell you how I use it:
🗄The first five drawers are dedicated to days of the week: Monday-Friday and I make copies a week in advance and put them in the drawer for the day I’ll be using them.
🗄 Main copies I need to make copies with go in my “Copy” drawer for safe keeping until I made it to the copy room to do my prep work.
🗄 Any work that I collected and needed to grade went into my “Grade” drawer.
🗄 All the graded work that was ready to file and go home in take home folders was put into my “File” drawer.
🗄 Anything else that needed a home, but didn’t fit into any other category went into my “Misc.” drawer aka my junk drawer—hey, we all have one! 😂
Planner:
📒 I use sticky notes to keep track of to do lists, reminders, and collaborative groups I’ve made—these end up on my planner, in my planner, or fixed to my small group table 😂.
📒I plan curricular areas in different colors and in the schedule order they are on the schedule. I use the SAME colors to write down the copies or supplies that I need to prep for each curricular area in the Saturday and Sunday spaces. I (almost always) plan a week in advance to give me time to prep materials.
**I am not required to turn in detailed lesson plans. If I need to make such lesson plans, I have a template I use.**
📒 Finally—here is a snap of what my planner ACTUALLY looks like after a week of planning. It’s messy, there is a lot of short hand, white out, cross outs, notes, and checks—but it works for me!
•
What are you favorite planning and organization hacks?

I’ve been getting a lot of DM‘s asking about what recommendations I had for teachers to grow their classroom library in intermediate grades. **Zoom in to see the titles!**
First, I want to shout out teachers who I’ve gathered recommendations from because they’re the real MVPs.
First, Vera from @thetututeacher and her book page @diversereads has a ton of incredible Book recommendations for educators K-8. She also has a book list available for purchase on her teachers pay teachers which I have bought and it has been an incredible resource!
Second, Andrea from @theliteracyjunky is constantly buying, Reading, reviewing, and recommending books over on her page. I’ve gotten so many titles from her recommendations!
Finally, I wanted to invest in my library over the course of last year and @wambookbundle was the perfect way to do it. I was on a monthly subscription where I would receive two brand new books in the mail each month. These books are carefully vetted and come with a handout of standards that could be used with each book.
Shout out to @mrs.s4success for introducing me to WAM!
•
My book vacation box came in handy when packing up my classroom! All of these wonderful texts are currently in storage for the time being ❤️.
•
Finally I wanted to support Mike from @thebookwrangler and his sentiment on skipping (and cutting down 😉) on the dollar spot this year and investing in your classroom library. Take a critical eye to the books in your library and ensure that your library is full of diverse texts that are not only mirrors for your students, but also windows to introduce them to cultures, experiences, and identities that are different than their own. 
#diversifyyourlibrary 📚

So…I wrote a book!
It’s called Be the Flame Sparking Positive Classroom Communities it’s linked in my stories and will be on my LinkTree (link in bio!)
🔥
Be the Flame is geared towards educators K-6 and describes activities and ideas to help build community within different realms of education: with your students one-on-one, among your students as a class, with families, with teammates and staff, and with other teacher in the social media community.
🔥
My hope with this book is to demystify the relationship building practice for newer teachers and give new ideas for veteran teachers to try out in their rooms. We, as educators, are the flames that draw others in. I hope this book sparks the excitement for community within its readers.
🔥
 Better yet, you’ll also read about amazing ideas from educators you may know from this community who are featured within the chapters:
@caffeinateandeducate, @jillianstarrteaching, @blackandbrightin2nd, @the_renewed_teacher, @teaching3rdwithmrg, and @kindcotton 
🔥
There is an excitement and nervousness about putting yourself out there like this and I hope it is something that can resonate with you all.
This has been a labor of love over these past ten months—but I am humbled have it published. Big thank you to @casas_jimmy and @jzoul for supporting me through this processes and believing I had something worth sharing.
#BeTheFlameEDU
